f the Paladins of Mar, as well as the deeds of the Steel Warriors.  And I also read about the beauty of the Women.  Freeport then wasn't the cesspit that it is now.  It was the hub of trade for Antonica.  Eurdite Caravans would leave daily from Qeynos in route to Freeport to trade with the Elven, Gnomish and Dwarven artisans.  These caravans where rarely harassed due to the many Barbarian Mercenaries that the Merchants would hire for the trade routes.  Not to mention the still capable Armies of Antonica, and Karana that ranged the plains, and trade routes.  All this would change however.  <br>
  It was during this trip that I first met a Halfling.  I was amazed at their smallness.  When I first encountered the little person, I was in Highhold keep attending a political function. The King was an arrogant bastard I thought.  He was so sure of the security of his hold that he was not even willing to see the trade delegation from Halas.  Since Halas is so remote, we don't have much in the way of trade.  Oh we do a fair trade with Qeynos, and the Glade, but when it came to Euriden, and Freeport.  We didn't have anything to sell accept for troops.  So we of Halas have become a race of Warriors, and mercenary's.  In those times of peace our economy was in need of renewal, and fast.  The people of Halas were not starving yet.  Nor did we have beggars in the streets. (Not a trade encouraged in Halas)  The Elders knew that in order for the Wolves of the North to thrive in the newworld, there must be trade other then Mercenaries.<br>
 The dinner party had become boring at best, and I ventured into the pass to sit near the sparkling lake not far from the keep.  I was thinking of the young human woman I met at school.  We would often go walking in Qeynos hills before dawn do discuss poetry, nature, and music.  All things that I wasn't very interested in at the time.  Well, all except for poetry.   I knew poetry was the way to a woman's heart.  And my being a young Barbarian at a human collage I found it to my advantage to learn all I could on the subject. It turned out; I had a knack for it.  So this young Noblewoman found my company entertaining.  Or so I told myself at the time. It turned out to be me who was smitten though.<br>
<br>
   Arianna Q'Tonoth was a black haired minx as her father described her.  She had already turned down just about the entire Guard force of Qeynos of various marriage proposals, and was now working her way through the ranks of the collage of Qeynos.  Until she met the hulking man from Halas, she never felt intimidation from men.  She studied the arcane arts, and was from a long, line of wealthy Wizards, and Enchanters.  So she normally let a man carry on for a while, then dispose of them.  Men knew better then to attempt to force their way on a wizard.  <br>
  Gavin was smitten with her from the first.  He had his choice of the women at school, but Arianna's fire attracted him.  She was outspoken, and didn't play the usual girl games of subtle hints, and teases.  She just walked up to the giant, and said: &quot; Well, are you going to ask me for a walk, or not?&quot;  <br>
Gavin for the first time in his life didn't have a thing to say.  He looked at her, and just held out his arm.  That was the first evening that the couple strolled into the hills along the Western Sea.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Hey, whatcha doing Mister?&quot; came a high child like voice from Gavin's left.  He stood up from his position on the ledge of the falls, and looked around.  He didn't see anyone, so he sat back down, thinking he heard an echo.  Then there was a tug on his sleeve, and he looked to his right, there she was.  I thought that this person was a child, she was so small, so I said.  <br>
&quot;Good evening child, why has your parents let a bundle like you get so far from home?&quot;<br>
&quot;Hey, I am no child Barb Brain, I am a Halfling.  The master race of all Norath.&quot;  With that she scampered off on her little feet, and was gone. Or so I thought.  I stood up, and went to the inn at the base of the falls, and decided it was time for an Ale.  As I entered the tavern I noticed that I had been robbed.  There was nothing I could do about it now, so I turned back to the rooms I shared with the rest of the delegation in the Keep.  As I was walking this pocket thief scampered up to me again.  She ran past me, and stopped just ahead on the path and held my change purse in her hand.  With a little impish grin, and the twinkle of mirth in her eye she said; &quot;Here's your purse barb brain.  You should carry gems instead of those Qeynos coppers.  How is a girl supposed ta earn a livin?&quot;  With that she tossed my purse to my feet, and ran off again.  I could not bring myself to call the constable; as a matter of fact the whole event had me so amused, that I began staggering in gales of laughter.  Once again the little bundle accosted me while I was leaning on a wall trying to regain my composer.  &quot;What's so funny ya big oaf?  You'll be causing an avalanche with all that racket.&quot;<br>
  I could not reply. I was so caught up in my laughter that I just sat down, and offered the little thief a swig of my flask.  She accepted it, and sat down before me just out of reach.  She took a long pull from the flask, and smacked her lips, and stood up again.  &quot;I am Shalia, since you have made it impossible for me to work tonight, you could at least let me know your name.&quot;<br>
I finally recovered enough to respond from my laughter to respond.  I stood up, and bowed with a flourish to the little woman; which caused her to jump back a ways.  <br>
&quot;I am Gavin Macalaister of the Clan Macalister at your service my lady.&quot;<br>
Now it was the Halfling's turn to laugh.  I was a bit taken aback at the intensity of this small person's mirth since I was being formal.  I should have known from my studies that halflings took almost nothing seriously.  But me being the young barbarian fresh from the Qeynos University, I forgot to take this into account.  Which of course caused my small friend to roll around on the ground before me in gales of laughter.  The more embarrassed I became, the more she laughed.  If ever you find yourself becoming big headed.  I suggest a trip to Rivervale to regain your humility.  Well, once Shalia composed herself, she told me that no one; much less a barbarian from Halas had ever bowed to her.  She removed a loaf of black bread from her pack, and offered me a piece.  Which was also a lesson I should have studied more closely.  It seems that in Halfling society if a woman offer's a man her bread….Well, I will let you guess the rest.  To make a long story short.  I was able to back out of an awkward situation stating that I was betrothed and to ignorance of the ways of the vale.  However she insisted that she would accompany me in my travels for a time until she got bored.  If I knew what I know now, I would have called the guard on the spot. That little woman caused the majority of my gray hair I believe, well, Her, and Ardin.  <br>
  We finished our late night snack, and headed back to my rooms.  I awoke in the morning to the laughter of my traveling companions.  It appeared that my newfound friend had snuggled up to me in my sleep, and my fellow delegates found the picture hysterical. Well, Shalia not to be out done hopped from the bunk (fully clothed) and stated that the night was much to her liking.  After a great many comments on how good it must feel to have been able to please the &quot;insatiable appetite of a Halfling&quot; my companions began to pack for the second leg of our journey.  <br>
  Personally I was relieved to be on my way.  The aloofness of the High court to the Halas trade delegation was still on our minds as we descended into the Kithicor Forest.  Our caravan wound its way through the forest with little incident.   Our new escort lead by the Freeport Militia, had consisted of 2 troops of Cavalry, in addition to our already sizable contingent of Halas Mercenaries seemed to be enough to discourage the Sharlok Orcs that had been more active in the forest lately.<br>
  My newfound friend chattered her way into the hearts of all around her as we traveled.  She rode most of the way on my shoulders, and annoyed me by telling everyone that I was her hired manservant.  This of course made her the talk of the caravan, and me the laughing stock.  Considering that she was not only a woman, but a Halfling there was no way for me to rid myself of this new burden, and maintain face so I resided to endure this inconvenience. <br>
  By evening we had made our way to the western portion of the Freeport commons, and set up our camp for the night.  The Militia scouts reported that there had been a raid the day before by some unknown assailants on the commons, and suggested that we post a double guard for the night.  Since the Mercs were tired after the long journey, the Halas delegation chipped in on the duties.  I awoke that night to Shalia jabbering about something happening outside the large tent we shared with the rest of the delegation, and I should arm myself.  I could hear shouting, and the sound of people running.  I pulled on my leather traveling tunic, and armed myself with my sword.  Just as I was about to exit the tent one of the Halas mercenaries burst through, and shouted &quot;Raid!&quot; and ran out again.  I followed, and discovered that there were torches lining the hilltop above our camp.  There must have been hundreds of them.  Shalia hoisted herself to her favorite perch on my shoulders, and whistled.  &quot;I guess I should have headed back to the vale when I had a chance.  Those are dervish cut throats up there. And lots of them.&quot;  I also noticed that our militia escort was no were to be found......<br>
<br>
More to come.  <br>
