  On the hill before us the bandit host prepared it self,and worked their way into a frenzy for the first charge.  Withno sign of the Militia the host charged.  With torches blazing,and glinting from tattered armor, and weapons of all types themulti raced bandits came.  The first few of them were felledhandily by the lead ranks of the Barbarians, as we returned theirwar cries with that of our own.  The blood in my veins boiled,and I was eager for the first bit of flesh upon my sword.  Theranks before me held however, and bandits retreated to regroup.The casters blasted many among the ranks of the bandits as theyretreated, and others were frozen in their tracks.  My countrymendidn't allow these later souls to escape, and demonstrated thewarrior code of our homeland by giving them a quick death.  TheBandits reformed on the hill once more.  This time however wecould hear the horns of cavalry to our left flank, and I couldsee the plumed helmets of Militia approaching at a charge.  Therewas something wrong I noticed.  While the Eurdines prepared towelcome the oncoming cavalry, we of the infantry ranks couldsee that this charge was for real, and aimed at us.  <br>
 &quot;FORM BLOCKS TO THE LEFT!!!&quot;  came the bellow of the MercenaryCaptain.  The disciplined Mercs scattered, and reformed in theclassic block formations to repel the cavalry charge.  The Northmen worked with the skilled precision of the warrior race thatwe are.  We formed the blocks in mere seconds, and just in timeto engage the Militia charge.  The cavalry fell on us with acrash of steal, and the screaming of war horses.  The outwardranks lowered spears, lances, and long swords that caused someof the horses to shy away.  The few that did not impaled themselveson the steal of Halas.  The riders could not offer resistanceafter being unhorsed, and were quickly dispatched by the Northmen.  Once the cavalry commander realized that he was dealingwith trained professionals and not a mere rag tag guard madeup of simple street thugs he called in his troopers to regroup.The Cavalry then rode to the hill were the Bandits surveyed thebattle, and it became obvious that the 2 units were going toattempt a combined effort this time.  The merc captain shoutedout yet another formation, and the north men scurried to formranks facing the enemy again.  The bandits once again workedtheir way into a frenzy on the hill by shouting insults, andhowling screams at the awaiting mercenaries.  A massive orc movedto the front of their mob, and hurled a spear at the front ranksas the mob came charging down the hill.  The Eurdines among theranks of the North men began to cast their spells of destruction.Shalia climbed down from my shoulders, and disappeared, or atleast so I thought.  I had no time to look for her since justthen the cavalry charged as well.  The forward ranks engagedthe bandits with yet another crash, and the blood curdling howlsof the Halas battle cry.  The cavalry hit our right flank thistime, and I knew that I would finally blood my sword.  The northmen on the right flank turned to the cavalry, but the forwardranks were swept under the charge, but not before slowing themso that we of the center could counter with a charge of our own.We surged forward unhorsing, and slashing our way through theMilitia cavalry as fast as possible.  The men of this light horseunit had misjudged the men of Halas for the their last time.As we moved through them I was pleased to feel my sword strikemy enemies in battle.  I don't know if it's in our blood, nordo I imagine that I am a warrior at heart, but there is somethingabout battle that makes a man feel more alive, and the surgewas within me.  I felled foe after foe, and my sword arm felttireless.  My comrades, and I surged through the petered chargewith the fury of the Tribunal.  Once again the cavalry commanderrealized his mistake, but this time it was to late.  We of thenorth fell on his troopers with no mercy.  I had no time to lookto my left to see how the forward ranks were dealing with thebandit infantry.  But from the screams, and explosions comingfrom that area, I could sense that the forward ranks were holding.<br>
  Finally my little companion made her appearance.  Justas I thought to have finally engaged a foe worthy of me, sheappeared behind the Hulking Ogre that I was engaged with.  Islammed the foul beast with all my might, but the creature onlygrinned at me, and delivered a blow that shattered my alreadytattered shield.  I was able to parry his next attack, and counterwith a slash across his midsection.  To my surprise the massivecreature only laughed at me again, and struck me with a blowto my right shoulder that brought me to my knees.  Just thenShalia screamed, and jammed her daggers into the back of theOgre.  With a surprised look, he turned to face his new enemy.I can't remember much about what happened next, but my comradestold me later that I went into some sort of rage.  I guess Ipicked up a sword from the ground, and began cutting my way intothe bandits, and Militia with the blood fury that is known toour kind.  The shaman called it the divine will of the Tribunal,while others called it beserker rage.  It's happened to me sinceon many occasions but I still can't say that I understand it.The Ogre was a distant memory that faded into a melange of battlescenes running their way through my mind that night.  I rememberShalia shouting at me, and I also remember a Shaman waving ahand above me.  But there isn't much more.<br>
  I regained mysenses sometime close to dawn, and was surprised to find thatI was no where near our camp.  I stood up, and winced at thepain of my wounds.  I looked my self over, and I could see thatsomeone had taken the time to set bandages on the worst of mywounds.  My shoulder was in a sling, and my armor in ruins, andcovered in dried blood.  I was a mess.  I noticed that therewere several other warriors, and trade delegates sleeping nearwhere I awoke.  I noticed that these men were also wounded insome cases it appeared to be mortally.  There was a female shamanmoving among the wounded, and with her was a wood elf girl ofstunning beauty.  She was playing a loot, and it seemed thatjust the sound o her music was healing the wounded.  Just asI was about to introduce my self, I felt a tug on my kilt.  <br>
&quot;Hey!, it's about time you woke up you oversized fruitcake&quot;  I looked down to see Shalia standing to my right posedin a stern stance with her hands balled in fists at her hips.I smiled at the sight since she reminded me of spoiled girl thathad been denied an expensive doll.  <br>
&quot;Just what areyou smiling at Barb Brain!?!.  I suggest you sit your big buttdown before I take a bite out of your knee!.   You scared mehalf to death with your shenanigans last night, and I am notabout to let you go opening those wounds again after it tookme so long to bandage you up.  NOW SIT!&quot;  I looked at mysmall friend, and was surprised to see that she was on the vergeof tears.  &quot;I think she means it brother.&quot; Came a voicefrom my left.  I looked to see an older north man laying on amat to my left.  He was wounded severely, but he looked at mewith the eyes of a man content with himself.  He spoke again.<br>
&quot;Lad, you almost got yourself killed last night withthat rage you went into.  That little one there saved your life.I suggest you listen to her.&quot;  I sat once more with my backto the tree.  Shalia made a &quot;humph&quot; sound, and scamperedover to where the Shaman, and bards were healing the wounded,and comforting those that have reached the end of their journey.The old warrior turned his head to me, and smiled.  <br>
&quot;I seen you last night lad.  You have the fire.  But you haveto learn to control it.  After you felled the bandit commanderyou ran off after the retreating Bandits.  If it were not foryour little friend convincing a Shaman to root you, you wouldbe the main course on an Orc fire right now.&quot;  I lookedback at the old veteran.  &quot;I don't remember older brother,I blacked out after that Ogre struck me with his war hammer.&quot;  I told the veteran.  &quot;Well Lad, you can probablyexpect to be recognized for your stupidity since you are theone that killed the bandit Commander.  But remember you had alot of help from that little thief friend of yours over there.So don't go and get a big head.  You need a great deal of training.Last night you got lucky.  I suggest that you get your ugly arseback to Halas post haste.&quot;  I was both shocked, and stungby the veteran's words.  I knew that I carried my clan name withhonor during the night, but I had no idea that my rage almostgot me killed, nor did I know that the Ogre I was engaged withwas the Bandit commander.<br>
Hell, at that point, I still wasn't sure if we had carried the day or not.  I look again to theold warrior to tell him that I was not in fact a warrior by trade,but he had died.  I look at his remains for over an hour beforeShalia returned, and covered the veteran's face.  She lookedtired, and very sad.  It was getting on in the day, and the sunwas getting close to noon.  &quot;Gavin, we have to get movingsoon or we will not make the city before night fall.&quot;  Ilooked at Shalia in shock.  &quot;City?!  We were just attackedby the city militia, what makes you think I am going on to thatcity?&quot; Shalia looked again into my eyes, and said &quot;Gavin, those were not the true militia.  Our real escort wasfound dead by some scouts of  Tunare this morning while you weresleeping.   They were all found with their throats cut, and strippednaked.  The bandits came from the deserts, and ambushed themin their camp before they ever linked up with the Caravan.&quot;As she finished, several carts were pulled to up to our littleaid station by a group of peasants.  The Shaman, with the helpof a few bards, and some of the walking wounded started to placethe worst off of us into the carts for the journey to Freeport.My original excitement about this journey was all but gone. Now I only wished for the warm embrace of Arianna, and sweetmusic of Qeynos……<br>
