&quot;Thank you, brave men of Halas.&quot;<br>
  To this warrior, would be diplomat.  That is thanks enough.  But that would not be the case.  Once the Halas trade delegation, and the Merchants for the caravan heard that the carts of wounded were approaching the city, a party of warriors, and healers were sent to escort the little wagon train through the city to the fair.  Shalia whistled as I was met with a flourish of salutes, and bows from the members of the Steel Warriors, and of the Wolves of the North that met our party.  Apparently there was a bit of over celebration, and exaggeration that went on once the Trains of the Caravan arrived in the city, and the tails were told in the Taverns, over tankards, and bottles.  My deeds were now of legend although slight in my memory.  My little friend, and I were brought before the elite of Freeport, and heralded as the Heroes that saved the western Caravan.  Shalia was not one to shy away from fame, and made sure that all there knew her role in the battle.  I thought it comical when she was approached by the little delegation from the Vail, and asked to tone it down a bit.  I think that was the only time I had ever seen her humbled.  <br>
I on the other hand was asked to do pretty much the opposite by my fellow delegates.  It seemed to them that I should not only be proud of my performance in my first battle, but that I should help our cause by boasting our prowess.  I found the boasting difficult.  I am not suited to it, and I also felt ashamed.  I knew that my role was minor at best during the battle.  I also knew that my comrades were stung that I, and not the Mercenary Captain was chosen to be the so called Hero.  But being men of Halas, they did not voice their disagreement openly.  Instead they talked among themselves about it. Soon, I was no longer welcome at the tables of the rank, and file among them.  This is what bothered me the most.  I am after all a simple man, and to be shunned by my fellows was severe punishment for someone else's idea of fame.  It was then that I decided that politics was not to my taste, and bid farewell to the trade delegation.  After spending a week in Freeport, I left my Inn in the middle of the night, and took ship to Feydwer.  I was paid handsomely for my part in the Caravan's defense, much to my surprise.  So I decided that I should take my studies to the City's of the Fey, Hammer, and Tinker's box.  I wrote Arianna a lengthily letter, bringing her up to date, as well introducing her to the rumors that I was sure she was hearing regarding my new traveling companion.  I also asked her to join me.  I knew that asking a woman to brave the wilds of Antonica would normally offend, and even cause some women to forget about you.  But this was Arianna.  She was a wizard of skill, not to mention a woman with more grit then most men that I have met.  She would be offended if I didn't ask. <br>
<br>
  I wasn't surprised to find out that Arianna had made it to Feydwer ahead of the ship, and was waiting for us in the Wood Elf City of Kelethin.  She wrote of a terrible war that was being fought there in the hills, and that of an Orc strong hold called Crushbone.  Shalia not being able to read hovered around me like a fly over a carcass.  She would not let me be until I finally read letter to her.  Arianna wrote of the regiments of Elves that left for the hills daily to engage the Orcish hordes.  She also wrote of a race long thought dead.  The Tear'Dal.  She wrote that the Tear'Dal Dark Elves had emerged from there subterranean strong holds, and were now making a move to retake their former homelands. <br>
  As Shalia and I traveled through the Butcher Block Mountains we could see the evidence of the war being fought in Greaterfeydark.  The dwarves were mobilizing, and there was much activity in the, and around Kaladim.  We arrived at the Dwarven strong hold on our second day in Feydwer, and we were welcomed heartily to my surprise.  The dwarves had hired two regiments of Barbarian Warriors, and were so pleased with their fighting prowess that even a man that was merely of the same race was welcomed into their homes with out question.  The city to me was very uncomfortable however.  Despite every attempt by our hosts to make it otherwise.   Everywhere I went in the stout home of the Dwarves, I had to duck, crawl, and crouch.  Needless to say, it was a humbling experience.  We stayed with the Dwarves for a few days, and then set out for Greaterfeydark dark in the wake of a departing Dwarven Infantry Regiment heading for the lines.  We followed along with the trains of the Regiment to their first rest stop some 15 miles out of Kaladim before the hearty warriors stopped for lunch.  I was impressed with the pace of the small warriors, they kept to a trot almost the entire distance, and I didn't hear one complaint from the line troops.  I thought this to be particularly impressive for all soldiers know that there is no such thing as a soldier that doesn't bitch about something.  But there was a quiet purpose to these small men of oak.  They knew what was to come.  The losses from the lines were heavy.  These men faced it with quiet determination, and a bravery that I have only seen in my homeland.  It was comforting to see this brother race of stout hearts, and it was a pleasure to travel with them.  <br>
  After lunch the Dwarves packed up their trains, and started out at a brisk trot east to the frontier.  Shalia, and I kept pace to along with them, and were asked to join the lead officers at the front of the column.  The Commander briefed us on what was to come at the border as we ran, and informed us that a large Orc raiding Party had flanked a Woodelf light infantry battalion, and was now at the outskirts of Butcherblock.  He, and his unit were on a mission to intercept them before they could get behind the Elven, and Dwarven lines and disrupt their supply trains.  He also told us a little of how the Orcs were never organized until this new offensive started last month.  Now the Orcs were well organized, and lead in a way that proved to the Dwarves, and Elves alike that there was a new leadership driving the Orcs, and this could only mean that the Dark Elves had finally returned.  I found this disturbing taken with what I read in Arianna's letter.  I had always thought that the Dark Elves were just creatures of fiction used to scare children with.  Now the evidence was clear.  They did exist, and they have now returned.  Arkis, the Dwarven Paladin in command of the Dwarven regiment ask us to reconnoiter for him during their next rest stop that evening.  Eager for something useful to do, and to help our new-found friends, we took up the mission and set out to the frontier.  Since I do not see as well as a Halfling, Shalia took up point, with me tagging along behind her.  If we encountered trouble, I would be the muscle, and her the flanker.  Our plan was to avoid trouble at all costs though.  <br>
  We moved slowly through the forest in the direction of the frontier.  Shalia would slink silently away into the darkness, and return every so often to lead me to a new area.  We reached the frontier of Greaterfey in this hop scotch manner shortly before midnight without encountering anything of note.  Once at the frontier though it was obvious that there was something of profound evil in the area.  The air took on a stale sent and became noticeably colder.  The sounds of the small creature of the forest were gone now, replaced with low growls, and painful moaning.  I am not a man given to fear, but there was something here that was very wrong.  I was scared out of my wits.  Shalia was scared too, and that was unlike her.  We traveled carefully, and quietly for about another mile before we came upon something that will haunt me until the end of my days…<br>
