ire lad&quot; Remembering this, I relaxed my sword arm, and maintained my observance.  I would not sit long however.  I am guessing that the moon was at it's high point when I heard a blood curdling screech from the other side of the camp that I was watching.  I perked up to see what was going on, and what I saw both shocked, and horrified me.<br>
  From the darkness inside the tent that contained the hooded figure a large skeleton emerged carrying a small eleven babe.  The skeleton was followed by a separate figure that seemed to be controlling the foul creature.  The figure came into the light of the fire and I could see that it was a creature that I have never seen before, and later I learned that this was one of the dreaded Tier'Dal Necromancers that I had heard so many horror stories about.  I was so enraptured, and horrified that I did not notice Shalia sneak up beside me.  She tugged on my kilt, and almost caused me to jump out of my skin.  Once I looked down to meet the eyes of my small companion I could see that her face was ashen, and her eyes bright with terror.  She had seen something terrible that was sure, but we were on a mission, and I was going to complete it.  Shalia, motioned for me to leave with her, and there are times in my nightmares that I wish I had.  <br>
  Just as I turned back to the scene before me there was yet another scream from the babe as the skeleton broke off one of it's legs and handed it to it's master.  From within the tent there was the sharp sound of a sword striking bone at the same time.  From within the tent a head rolled to the feet of the foul Tier'Dal who looked down at it.  He turned the head so that it could see the bloody limb in his hand and shrieked. &quot; SEE WHAT BECOMES OF YOUR CHILD WITCH OF TANARE!!!&quot;  &quot;SEE WHAT INORRUCK DECREES FOR YOUR WEAKLING RACE!!&quot;<br>
The Tier'Dal then devoured the limb, and reached for another.  I could see now that the head was that of a High Eleven woman.  Her Eyes were wide open, and her mouth agape in a silent scream.  It was all I could do to keep from retching as the dark elf proceeded to devour the rest of the babe.  I could now see that the figure on the spit was also an Elf from the size of its frame.  Shalia was now frantic as she pulled on my kilt to go.  I slowly began to back away from the grizzly scene before me, and began to follow her.  It wasn't long before we reached the frontier again.  Still shaking with fear Shalia and I returned to report our findings to the Commander of the Dwarven infantry regiment.  But just before I entered Arkis's tent I could here a whisper invade my thoughts.  It was a foul, and hollow voice and I knew that it must be that of one of the Tier'Dal that attended that horrible scene.  <br>
&quot;Bear witness to your future Barbarian for what you have seen will be your end&quot;<br>
  Arkis became almost irrational as Shalia, and I described the horrible details of the night's recon. <br>
&quot;I never cared much for the snooty high Elves, but this is an atrocity that can not go unpunished by Kaladin I shall avenge the Elven Woman!&quot;  Arkis called for his troops to muster, and prepare for battle.<br>
  The Dwarven infantry were prepared to depart within an impressive 5 minutes of the first drum.  The lines of warriors among them were standing at attention as the Clerics trooped the lines in the same manner as the Shamans of Halas.  It was no wonder that the dwarves found barbarians like me so amicable.  They were just a smaller version of the men from Halas, and no less fearsome.  After the Clerics had finished with their blessings Arkis sounded the advance.  He deployed his men on in a 3 Phalanx formation with one battalion to the front in rank while on either flank he had one formation in column.  The dwarves worked their way through the forest with speed, and precision that denoted there training.  This was no green unit.  These men were of the elite Kaladim Royal Guards.  It was impressive to watch from our position to the rear of the center formation as the Guardsmen advanced through the wood.  Shalia was not impressed however.  She commented on the noise the dwarves were making, and there their pretty formation better be prepared for an ambush.  <br>
  It came with lightning speed.  One minute we were marching to contact with the Dwarves, the next we were in the middle of a pitched battle.  The Orcs fell on us from all sides.  Shalia, and I were caught in the middle of the fray, I was hard pressed to keep us both alive.  Two Orcs were on me, and I could see Shalia hiding behind a tree waiting for her chance to dart in.  The 2 Orc Legionaries were pressing me hard, and my new shield was already in ruins.  The first Orc launched a vicious set of sword strokes aimed at my head while the other attempted to get behind me.  I countered with a bash to the 2nd Orc, and struck him with a stunning blow. As he stood there shaking off my strike Shalia finished him with a perfect strike to his spine.  He then fell one his face trembling in death.  I didn't have time to congratulate Shalia however.  With my shield gone now, I was hard pressed to keep the other legionnaire from gaining an advantage.  My attacker was weakening I noticed, and he began to show an opening, on his left side.  I countered, and launched an attack of my own.  I fainted to his right, and he winced while trying to counter.  I then bashed him in the face with my shieldless left for arm and then ran him through with the remains of my longsword.  He slid from my sword clutching his midsection.  Shalia and I were now surrounded by the battle as the Orcs pressed the Guardsmen from all Sides.  I could see Arkis at the head of the center Phalanx engaging a dark figure as they both shimmered in strange light; I looked from him to the right flank and could see the Dwarves were being overwhelmed.  I grabbed Shalia and ran toward the left Phalanx commander to inform him that he must reinforce the right.  I didn't get 3 steps before I heard Shalia scream at my side.  She was surrounded in a green aura, and I could see blisters appearing all over her face.  I looked around to find her attacker, and seen a Dark Elf in the process of casting another spell.  I charged him, but a Skeleton warrior intercepted me.  I bashed the foul beast with my forearm, and the shoved it aside, I wanted that caster, and I didn't have time for this walking bone collection.  The caster unleashed his spell on me then.  I was momentarily surrounded in a white light, and I could feel that I was growing weaker, and I was slowed to a walk.  I fought to get at the caster but the Skeleton recovered from my stunning blow, and took a swipe at my back.  I turned on it again, and this time took its head with an overhand stroke from my sword.  The Skeleton now crumbled at my feet I turned once again to the caster just in time to see him unleash yet another spell.  This time I was surrounded in a green light, and I could sense fear, and panic creeping up on me.  I shook it off however, and continued my slowed advance.  Just as I was about to strike the evil Necromancer Shalia appeared behind him, and sliced open his neck.  His scream gurgled in his throat as he fell to the ground.  Shalia was hurt bad, and I could see that she was in immense pain.  I picked her up in my arms, and ran to where I thought the left Phalanx commander was with all the speed I could muster.  The sounds of battle were all around us.  As I ran I could hear screams, war cries, and explosions.  Evil spell casters were spewing forth the wrath of their foul gods on the Dwarven troops relentlessly, while the Dwarven Clerics struggled to keep the men in line, and healed for battle.  As we neared the embattled left Phalanx I could see that there would be little help from them.  They had collapsed in a tight block formation, and were fighting for their very lives.  Shalia and I barely evaded a charging Orc platoon as we looked for a place to rest and heal her wounds.  We retreated from the battle to a near by Hill.  I bandaged the worst of Shalia's wounds but I could see that she was still in poor shape and barely conscious.  I set her underneath a fallen tree, and then set out to rejoin the battle and to find a cleric that could better tend the wounds of my friend.  I prayed to the Tribunal that would not be to late.  As I approached the battle I could see that the left phalanx had defeated yet another Orc charge and were preparing to counter attack to releave the right.  I could not see the center Phalanx but I could hear that the battle was still raging in that direction.  The Left Phalanx began their charge, and I hurried to join them.  We surged toward were the right had been, and discovered that the Orcs were already gone.  What was left were the tattered, and bloody ruins of what was once the right phalanx of the regiment. The left phalanx commander left his clerics, and once again sounded the charge this time toward the center formation.  The Orcs there were still attempting to crush the block that the dwarves had fallen into. The battle desperate, the Dwarves fought as if the were already dead.  They were fearless and self-sacrificing as they protected their last Cleric who sat in the middle meditating.  The left commander simply screamed the war cry of Kaladim, and his soldiers charged behind him.  The Orcs were now the ones on the defensive as they were caught between the desperate and the tenacious.  With the 2 handed sword that I had taken from a fallen Legionnaire I cut my way threw the Orcs feeling the fire once again rise within me.  I made no move to defend.  I simply found a target, and attacked until there were no more Orcs.  I once again lost track, and again I found myself coming back to reality after the battle was over.  We had won, but barely.  Arkis lay dead with a wicked looking blade piercing his breastplate.  Near him were many slain Orcs, and 3 Dark elves.  He had died a hero's death.  I saluted his corpse, and went out to find a healer.  I had to be sure that Shalia was alright……<br>
