&quot;Gavin&quot; She called to me.  I opened my eyes and stood up from my prayers.  She lay with her head on Gaitalla's lap; her face no longer covered in blisters.  She reached up to me, and brought my face close to hers.  As I leaned over to get closer, I glanced at Gaitalla with a questioning look.  She returned my look with one of sadness.  It was all I could do to keep from breaking down.  I had to be strong for Shalia, now more then ever.  Shalia put her little arms around my neck, and whispered for me to take her into the forest for the last time.  I cradled her in my arms and walked numbly into the forest away from the grizzly battleground.  I walked until I came to a moss bank on a short cliff near a massive oak tree.  I sat down with my friend held close to me, and whispered her name.  Shalia was gone.  <br>
  I laid her down under the moss beneath the massive oak and I stayed near her grave for longer then I can remember.<br>
   I awoke suddenly in the bright sun to the tingling of a fairy playing near my face.  I came to my feet with a start as the fairy darted off frightened much the same as I.  The Fairy returned slowly, inching her way to me.  Once near to me again she asked in a voice I could barely hear.<br>
 &quot;Are you the man known as Macalister?&quot;<br>
&quot;I am.&quot; I replied in a low voice, not knowing what this creature wanted and wanting to be alone with my friend's grave. <br>
&quot;I have come to bring a message from Shalia.  Gavin of Halas, know that although you are betrothed.  Know that I loved you, and know that my time had come.  My god called to me, and now I am home.  Be well, and live free.&quot; I stared at the tiny being tingling before me amazed at her words, and her appearance.  She almost took on the shape of Shalia as she delivered her message, and her voice was that of Shalia.  Overcome, I knelt before the fairy, and bowed my head in submission, and asked for forgiveness.  But in Shalia's voice she reprimanded me for being a foolish barbarian.  She had been called she said.  There was nothing I could have done to stop her time.  Her message complete, the little fairy swooped down to my face, kissed my cheek and then disappeared into the forest.  I stood up then still unsure of what to do until a voice entered my mind that has been with me ever since.  <br>
&quot;Quit chor snivlin ya oaf, and get to Kelethin.  Your betrothed needs you&quot;  <br>
Shalia was even worse now then she was when she walked with me in the mortal world. <br>
She has been with me ever since that day.  Sometimes I think its the Tribunal's way of letting me know that I messed up somewhere along the way.  But I have to admit.  I would grieve her all the more if she were not with me in my dreams, and in my thoughts.<br>
I donned my tattered armor and weapons and headed east along a ridgeline overlooking the road to Felwyth.  I noticed that the traffic on the road was heavy and mostly military heading for the lines that the Dwarven Royal Guards had made secure with their sacrifice.  It seemed the campaign was heating up from the activity on the road.  It was about 3pm on my 7th day on the Island continent that I finally arrived at the tree City of Kelethin.  Once there I was amazed at the ingenuity of the Wood Elves as I rode one of the 3 lifts that brought me to one of the many platforms that made up the City Among the Leaves.  I have to say though that although Kelethin is a very Beautiful city, I found it almost as uncomfortable as Kaladim.  Due to the fact that the people of Kelethin are so slight in size, almost all of the doors were inaccessible to one of my race.  There were only 2 or 3 dwellings that I could actually access, and they were not available to the general pubic.  The ambassador from Halas was a Human named Jason Bartoff, who also doubled as the Ambassador for Antonious Bale.  Once I was able to contact him, I was directed to a make shift camp at the base of the city on the ground where all the Northmen were camped.  Once I found lodgings among my countrymen, I set out to find Arianna.<br>
  After speaking with the some of the Wizards of Felwyth I discovered that the Antonican Wizards had sent Arianna along with a few of her fellow Wizards along with a Regiment of Highelf Cavalry to the lines.  According to the Elf Wizard I spoke to, the Dwarven Infantry supported by a Mercenary Regiment from Halas had broken through the Orcish lines, and the Elvish Cavalry was sent to exploit the breach.  <br>
  After hearing this I made arrangements for to travel with a platoon of Woodelf scouts that were bound for the lines the next morning.  <br>
  That night I settled into my tent near the R&amp;R area of some of the same Mercenaries that I had traveled to Freeport with.  The men that I fought with so many weeks before had forgiven me my fame after our arrival at Freeport, and were genuine in there condolences for the lose of Shalia.  They played sad songs on the pipes, and toasted long into the night of the fearless little thief from the Vale.  I was once again among my brethren, and it did my heart good to know that they felt much the same about her that I had.  Many wept at my telling of her fearlessness in her final hour, and of her final resting-place in the wood.  That night was a turning point in my grief.  I swore a blood oath of Vengeance against the Orcs of Crushbone, and the Darkelves of Neriak along with many of my brethren.  The Shaman sealed the oath, and the Mercenary Commander released a platoon to me to carry out our oath.  We would depart as I had planned in the morning.  Although I planned to find my beloved Arianna.  This errand would have to take priority.  The honor of Halas, and of the Vale would be our cause, and Blood Vengeance of a fallen comrade. <br>
  I awoke before the dawn the next day.  I lit a small fire, and began to prepare for the days action.  This was the first time I had taken the blood oath, and I was careful to observe the right as I had been shown by my father.  I kneeled on the soft morning grass facing the northeast toward the lights of my homeland.  I lit the sulfur of the Caverns of Everfrost given to me by one of the Shaman of the Tribunal.  I prepared the colors of vengeance in a blessed Orc skull, and set to my rights, and prayers.  During the Ceremony as is custom, I was joined by 2 Shaman, and the Warriors who would join me on my quest.  All were already prepared for the journey.  In this tradition my people carried out our rights for over 2 thousand years.  On the walls of caves, and in the Mountains of Everfrost were the signs of my people's devotion to the 6 Hammers, and to justice.  We of the north regard justice above all else, and justice to a close friend, loved one, or family member wrongfully slain was a crime only atoned by death.  Shalia was all of these to me.  During the night she appeared before me just before I closed my eyes for some rest, and smiled her smile.  <br>
&quot; Don't ya be doing nothin stupid ya big oaf, and don't ya be thinkin you can take um all to yer self.  Let the warriors who are with you get a few too.  I will be with you always&quot;<br>
She shed a tear, and touched my cheek with her palm.  Then she faded. <br>
  I lay there on my cot for a few minutes before drifting off to sleep.  I slept soundly, and dreamlessly that night, and I awoke before the dawn refreshed, and feeling better then I think I had ever before.  I kneeled in prayer to the Mother of all for the morning, and to the 6 Hammers for the strength to carry the day.  <br>
It was not long before the Shaman who were to join us arrived to prepare me for my Blood Revenge Quest.<br>
We prayed, and I painted myself with the colors of Vengeance, and justice.  Once complete we were met with the warriors, and made our final preparations.<br>
  We departed with the platoon of Tunare scouts as planed, and marched through the day toward the lines of the embattled elves, and Dwarves.   The scouts told us that there were several reports of Orc raids to the rear of the Dwarvish lines that linked them to Kaladim, and it was suspected that there were some survivors of the large raiding party that attacked the Kaladim Royal Guards.  Something told me to start here so I informed the platoon leader of the Tunare scouts that we would travel the rest of the way on our own.  The platoon leader assigned one if his rangers to us for recon and wished us luck on our quest.  <br>
  We proceeded along the Western Frontier of the Greaterfeydark frontier following our scout.  Not long after dawn on the 3rd day we finally encountered signs that we were nearing our query, our scout picked up the trail of what appeared to be an Orcish party of at least 20.  We followed, and discovered a grizzly trail of religious sacrificial remains, and camp sites littered with bones, and bits of flesh left for the local carrion eaters. <br>
Once, we came into a site only an hour behind these vermin and had to ease the pain of a half eaten Dwarven woman. They just left her to die. The Shaman gave her potions to put her to sleep, and 2 warriors took her into the forest, and opened her veins so that she would die peacefully, and painlessly.  The Beasts that had attacked her made sure that she would not be healed.  They maimed her in the most unspeakable ways just for sport.  We spent another hour in the cam as I helped my 2 brothers prepare for the right of Vengeance in honor of the Woman.  The Orcs had much to atone for this day, and the Shaman made sure that the will of the 6 Hammers was with us.<br>
  NaunKa, our Ranger guide told us that the Orcs knew that they were being followed, but was puzzled that they didn't seem to care.  That night we found out why.  Naunka suggested that we follow at night from now on so that we could catch the Orcs by surprise.  We once again prepared for battle but this time before dusk.  We struck our fireless camp, and moved out swiftly, and quietly.  The Gods made the night Clear, and bright.  The moons were full, as the sound of screams shattered the peace of the night.  We could hear that the Orcs were preparing their evening meal.  We could here shouts, and pleas as we neared the camp.  To a Man the Mercs were ready to end the lives of these things that fed on sentient beings…..<br>
