 ability to almost become invisible against a back drop of star lit forest.  Our casualties began to mount as another of my comrades fell to his knees clutching his open midsection.  I renewed my effort, and attempted to taunt this Dark Avatar off of one of our younger warriors.  He turned on me, and brought all his dark powers to bear.  Two of my comrades took the moment, and engaged our evil foe from behind.  One of our Shaman cast a spell that caused that Dark Elf's skin to become frosted to the point that it was breaking off in flakes as I bashed, kicked, and slashed blow after blow on the Dark Elf's armored body, and head.  Now there were 4 of our party on the evil one.  The elf hissed insults at me as it became clear that it would be defeated.  My comrades, and I were wearing the abomination to the breaking point, but he still had some tricks up his sleeve.  The evil son of a Goblin seemed to be able to draw life from his enemies, and brought me to my knees once with a crushing spell that seemed to suck the very life from me.  Finally it took one of the Shaman to end his life with a damning spell from the Tribunal.  Once the Dark Knight was slain, we were able to mop up the remaining Orcs and lesser Dark Elves easily.   There was a prisoner's stable to the rear of the camp, and I was relieved to find my Arianna was still alive, although beaten severely, and covered in grime.  It was obvious that her ordeal had lasted for sometime.  She was barley conscious when I released from her shackles, and I could tell that she could not recognize me.  As she became aware that she had been released, she shrank away from me, and screamed again as I had heard upon our entering the camp.  The anger returned again as the image of what could have been the cause her screams.  <br>
  I kneeled before her and offered my water flask and a dry chamois.  She then looked at me, and slowly I could see her eyes light up in recognition.  At first it seemed as though she did not believe her eyes, and then  she began to shrink away again as if I were some evil being.  I have heard of casters known as enchanters that are able to twist one's mind, so I took my time.  The Warriors, and Shaman of my war party took the other prisoners out of the pen while I sat with my betrothed.   Arianna, look at me again, and it seemed that she was surprised that I had not become violent with her.  I just sat there with the water flask, and chamois before me.  Then I remembered.  She had never seen me in full battle gear, and war paint.  I took the chamois and began clearing away the blood, and war paint that covered my face, and hands.  As I worked to make myself recognizable, Arianna finally whispered my name in a quite, and questioning voice.<br>
&quot;Gavin?&quot;  Arianna, then surprised me, and threw her arms around me with a shout.  &quot;Gavin, it is you!  You came for me!&quot;  Arianna and I cleaned our selves as best we could with the water flask, now very stained Chamois.  Just as we were finishing; NaunKa entered with some Robes, and equipment.  Arianna composed herself, and stood from our little reunion and thanked the Ranger for her things.  &quot;NaunKa told us that he had found her robes, and equipment among the Shadow Knight's things in his tent.  He also told us that there was a Wizard's' tent there, but he did not see a Wizard among the dead.  &quot;Gavin, I think there is another party working from this camp.  We should prepare.&quot;  The ever serious faced woodelf said. <br>
&quot;Gavin, go to your friends. I must prepare myself to travel.&quot;  Her face now stern, and eyes averted as if something deep within her heart were troubling her and she could not bring it forward.  I left her to her preparations, but I could not help but to feel as though I were.  I knew that something terrible had happened to her, but I also knew that she would keep her own council.  I only hoped the she still felt as she did before I left for Freeport so long ago. <br>
  I didn't have long to ponder the current events of my personal relationships however.  NaunKa returned to the camp after a brief patrol of the area and reported that there were at least 15 Orcs, and 3 Dark Elves heading up the River toward the Raider Camp.  In a flurry we worked to hide the bodies, and set traps, and blinds for an ambush. During this time, Arianna, and 2 of her party members stepped into the center of the Camp, and demanded that blinds be set for them.  Angus MacTavish, one of the Warriors on the quest with me gave me a look of disapproval.  I nodded to him, and off he went to set the blinds.  Halas men had no problems with folks issuing orders, nor did they have problems following them.  But when some snooty Elf or human starts demanding things we are apt to get a little snooty back.  Usually snooty for us means a bust in the chops though.  Angus didn't like it, but he did his job.  As all of us did.  I pulled Arianna to the side as she turned to the 2 high elves that we rescued with her, and asked her why they were treating their saviors as though they were servants.  We didn't ask for much.  But a little appreciation was certainly in order.  Arianna turned on me then, and gave me a withering look that convinced me that this was not her.  <br>
&quot;Do not suppose that you can question me Barbarian.  Just do as your told&quot; I watched her follow her 2 friends to their blinds.  Then I called for the Shaman.  <br>
  Angus, brought the 2 Shaman, and NaunKa with him as he returned.  NaunKa reported that the Orc party was still at least 15 minutes out, and that we had time to deal with our current problem as well.  Gertrude, and Rolan Romtuk, our 2 shaman suggested that we set 2 traps.  One for the incoming party, and another for the one already here.  There was something strange about these 3.  Arianna, no matter what she had been through would never cast her lot with arrogant fools.  She spoke about such people often at the University, and on our walks in the hills of Qeynos.  I would never dream of betraying a loved one, but this could not be her.  I did ask my comrades to wait until there was at least more substantial evidence however.  <br>
  After our brief council we set in our blinds, and waited.  The party didn't take long.  Once again I noticed something strange. This Orc party didn't enter the camp.  Instead, they scouted the area around it as if they had just discovered it.  Also the manner in which they scouted was not Orcish.  Orcs were not known for stealth.  This party was good.  NaunKa reported that there were a few times that he thought that he would be discovered while he followed there party's scouts.  He suspected that this party was not as it seemed.  We waited for another hour before the Orc party entered the camp.  The first scouts came in slowly, and carefully.  Moving from tree to tree as they surveyed the camp for signs of an ambush.  They waited just past our first blinds, and motioned for more of their party to advance.  The Dark Elves that approached also seemed strange.  These Elves seemed larger then the ones that I had encountered so far.  There was definitely something wrong here. Then, with a rushing sound one of the Orc scouts was struck with a charge of light that completely engulfed him.  Gertrude and Romtuk then unleashed their ambush.  But not on the Orcs.  Instead they combined forces, and cast canceling magic on the 3 casters behind the blinds we set for them.  That's when the confusion really started.  A cloud of confusion rushed over me, and it seemed that I was not in control of my own body.  I was an observer from inside my own mind as I watched myself charge out from my blind and attack one of the Dark Elves entering the camp.  It seemed that I was alone however.  My comrades did not rush forward to join the battle as they had before.  I watched my self as I drew forth the great sword that I still carried, and brought it down on the Dark Elf.  There were explosions all around me then, and something was grasping my legs firmly to the ground.  As I felt myself regain control of my movement, I discovered that the Orc party was not an Orc party at all.  Instead they were a party of Human, Dwarven, and Elvish adventurers. They were staring at me in disbelief.  I was still confused however, then someone shouted my name, and I spun to face NaunKa.  &quot;Gavin!! Enchanters!!  We have been deceived!!&quot;  Just as NaunKa screamed his last words, he burst into flames, and fell to the ground.  My warriors, supported by our 2 shaman rushed for the blinds containing the Dark Elf casters.  Only one remained.  The woman laughed at us as she shimmered, but not for long.  Gertrude bashed the Dark Elven woman with her mace, and interrupted her casting.  She then made short work of the Dark Elf as we stood near.  The party of adventurers stood beyond us still looking confused.  I then noticed that my armor was scorched, and I was bleeding from what looked like thorn pricks all over my body.   I sat down on a log near by holding my head in disbelief.  Still confused on what had just occurred, and troubled at losing yet another brave soul.  I didn't see that some one was standing before me looking as if she had seen a ghost.  &quot;Gavin?&quot;  Reluctant to look up, and not trusting my self after the events that had just transpired, I continued to sit, and stare at the ground.  It's not an easy thing to have the Woman you love turn into a Dark Elf Enchantress before your very eyes.  <br>
&quot;GAVIN!,  Look at Me!&quot;   She shouted this time, and push back my forehead forcing me to look at her. It was her alright. This time there was no mistake. Behind her stood several familiar faces from Qeynos. My Party also joined the growing group who cheered as Arianna dragged me to my feet, and kissed me soundly. &quot;Now do you believe Gavin?&quot;………………………<br>
